---

<section id="stakes" class="py-[var(--spacing-section)] border-t border-slate-gray">
  <div class="max-w-7xl mx-auto px-6 lg:px-12">
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto" data-animate="headline">
      <h2 class="font-heading text-titanium-white mb-8" style="font-size: var(--text-fluid-4xl); line-height: 1.05; letter-spacing: -0.02em;">
        Here's what most muralists and sign shops won't tell you.
      </h2>
    </div>
    <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto space-y-6" data-animate="fade" data-animate-delay="1">
      <p class="font-body text-soft-gray" style="font-size: var(--text-fluid-base); line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);">
        Most muralists paint what they want to paint. They show up with a style and a portfolio, and your wall becomes another canvas for their vision. Your project is a surface for their art, not a story about your business.
      </p>
      <p class="font-body text-soft-gray" style="font-size: var(--text-fluid-base); line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);">
        Most sign shops work the opposite way. They care about volume and turnaround. They take your logo, print it on vinyl, and stick it to your building before they move on to the next job. Your project is a transaction, not a conversation.
      </p>
      <p class="font-body text-soft-gray" style="font-size: var(--text-fluid-base); line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);">
        Both produce work that looks fine. Nobody stops for it. Nobody remembers it. Nobody walks into your business because of it.
      </p>
      <p class="font-body text-titanium-white" style="font-size: var(--text-fluid-base); line-height: var(--leading-relaxed);">
        That is what happens when nobody cares about what the work should mean before they start making it.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
